			<ol class="comments-list clearfix">
						<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comment clearfix li-comment highlander-comment" id="comment-199931" data-comment-id="199931">
			<div class="div-comment" id="div-comment-199931">
				<div class="comment-meta clearfix">
					<div class="comment-author-avatar">
						<a class="avatar-placeholder" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6449b1a2315cbf5739c90829c9669279?d=retro&amp;s=55&amp;r=pg"></a>					</div>
					<div class="comment-info">
						<cite><a href='http://www.jrimagination.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Marty S</a></cite>
						<a href="http://paidcontent.org/2013/02/14/the-brainpickings-brouhaha-and-the-problem-with-affiliate-links/#comment-199931" class="comment-permalink">Thursday, February 14 2013</a>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="comment-content">
					<div class="comment-text">
						<p>You said, &#8220;e-commerce sites (primarily Amazon) … provide her with a payment if one of her readers clicks through.&#8221; Clicking through and making a purchase after clicking through are two different things (at least with Amazon). There&#8217;s no payment to the affiliate unless there&#8217;s a purchase made during that visitor&#8217;s session. This really should be clarified. </p>
<p>I, for one, would think that no one is twisting the arm of the purchaser. If they buy it&#8217;s entirely their choice. They are free to blow it off as well.</p>
					</div>
